Add a note about the output completion check

This may cause some issues when the process is marked as complete here.
The downstream processes that are not complete and waiting for another
datum packet will never get a completion stamp from this process and
will hang. So far, processes only have all required or all optional
output ports (excepting the heartbeat port which is handled differently)
and this is not an issue. When new processes crop up that do have
required and optional output ports, this must be addressed.

Swap weak references to be internal

Switching the weak reference around from the edges to the process allows
a few things:

  - No more separation between edge_ref and edge for new processes.
  - Improved performance since .lock() only gets called in exceptional
    cases.
  - Weak references are entirely internal (edge::priv is the only class
    that knows or cares).
  - Less things to wrap when adding an extension language.

Import plugins with global visibility

Unfortunately, Python has a weird tangle where modules don't link
libpython.so because if Python is built statically, there is no dynamic
library to link to, initializers and such cannot be satisfied. If Python
is built statically and libpython.so exists, then there can be duplicate
symbols.

If the module loader is loaded from C++ code and its call to
Py_Initialize is the one that actually starts the interpreter, then its
loading of libpython.so is behind a RTLD_LOCAL barrier that prevents
Python modules from having access to libpython.so.

using C types directly. This breaks on LP64 (where long is 64 bit; e.g.,
Linux) versus LLP64 (where long is 32 bit; e.g., Windows) 64-bit
operating systems.

Set configuration values directly

The `git remote add` command fails if the origin already exists. Also,
`git remote rm` fails if the remote doesn't exist. With shared source
trees, build trees all try to run the hooks-init target, failing because
they can't set the remote properly.

The solution implemented here is to just set the configuration values
that are cared about instead of using the convenience targets.

Add logic to check shared output port logic

A shared output port may only have at most one mutable input port
listening to it. Any number of non-mutable input ports may be connected,
but any mutable ports spoil the whole party. The reasoning is that since
the output data is shared among all readers of the port, if the process
with the mutate port runs first, it can result in the other receivers
from seeing its new data instead of the data the upstream actually
created.

specification (in which case, the guarantees the parsers make are

are allowed in port mappings in clusters and connection specifications.
They are not allowed in cluster or process names when declared in a
pipeline file.

Implement _reconfigure for process clusters

Clusters are allowed to overwrite read-only values on processes, but
only those that are directly owned by it or those which are provided by
the cluster by a mapping. Because of this, it can use the more
restricted reconfigure_with_provides method on processes.

Allow reconfiguring processes via the pipeline

Due to the fact that clusters can provide extra logic, we do not want
processes to be configured outside of the pipeline. The pipeline can
enforce that only the top-level processes are reconfigured which ensures
that configuration values trickle from the top down.

Allow passing new parameters through

Clusters don't necessarily know what the children class will do with new
parameters, so it cannot block them. In this case, any unknown
configuration values need to be allowed through.

To fix this, keys are filtered out from the passed in configuration if
they are for the process and not tunable rather than only requesting
keys which are for the process and tunable.

Pass the new configuration block through

The child processes of clusters may have tunable parameters which are
not known to the cluster, so the cluster cannot unilaterally decide
which keys get through to the children.

Split reconfigure block of child processes

Since the cluster allows a process to be reconfigured and overwrite its
read-only values, we need to split the call which has the given subblock
from the one which has been generated from the configuration mapping so
that the incoming configuration overwrites any other read-only values.

Keep existing configuration keys around

be reset, we need to move the existing keys which aren't being reset
into the new config structure.

Short circuit the case where there is nothing new

Setup for mapping configs from loaded clusters

Due to the fact that the cluster configuration format currently
implements map_config with the CONF provider, the tunable machinery
within process_cluster cannot be used (due to this information never
reaching the cluster class).

To fix this, any line which uses the CONF provider to request which is
requesting a parameter from the main cluster by name is used to create a
configuration mapping. Unfortunately, with the way things currently
work, some extra steps must be done to ensure that the cluster won't be
setting any values on the processes which are mapped.

Use defaulted destructors

Replace empty inline destructors with defaulted destructors, where
available (retaining the empty destructor otherwise). This potentially
permits additional compiler optimizations, as a defaulted destructor is
not quite the same thing as an empty destructor. (Particularly, a
defaulted destructor may be 'trivial', while an empty destructor is not
permitted to be considered 'trivial'.)

Fix virtual shadowing

Add explicit `using` declarations to import the base class overloads of
virtual methods for which only some overloads are overridden. This is
necessary for all overloads to be visible via the subclass type (and
fixes `-Woverloaded-virtual` warnings).

Fix initialization order

Rearrange the members of `match_features_homography` so that the
d-pointer is first, as we normally (and want to) initialize it first.
This ensures ensures that the order in which initializations appear in
the source matches the actual order generated by the compiler (fixing a
`-Wreorder` warning).

Add helper to iterate over sparse matrices

Add a helper class that turns an Eigen::SparseMatrix into something that
we can trivially iterate over (e.g. with VITAL_FOREACH) in order to
visit all non-zero cells.

The choice of "enumerate" for the helper function is from the dictionary
definition, "to specify each member of a sequence individually in
incrementing order" (https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/enumerate).

Add unit test of sparse matrix enumeration

Add a unit test for the sparse matrix enumeration helper that was added
in the previous commit. This sets up some sparse matrices and performs
takes a sum and sum-product of the matrices [with another "matrix"], in
the manner of image filtering by convolution kernel.

And... it fails, due to a bug in the enumeration helper. This, kids, is
why we write unit tests!

Fix sparse matrix enumeration

Fix bugs in the sparse matrix enumeration helper. For some cases, the
outer vector may contain empty inner vectors, which require us to
immediately check the inner iterator for validity (as it can be
constructed invalid). Modify logic (both the increment operator and
constructor) to check if a newly constructed inner iterator is invalid
and, if so, to immediately increment until we get a valid one (or reach
the end).

Add function to read shared config

Add an overload of read_config_file to read one or more configuration
files (optionally merging contents) from standard shared data locations.
This can be used to read config files distributed with an application,
while providing a mechanism for the user to override settings in the
same.

For now, the caller is responsible for specifying the install prefix of
the executable using this function. This is because determining the same
is non-trivial, and because frankly the only implementation for doing so
that I fully trust is from Qt. (Fortunately, the immediate intended user
of this is the MAP-Tk GUI, which means we can use Qt for this.)

Add method to establish new logger factory.

Don't elide type in default parameter

GCC 4.4 (which we're still trying to support) supports uniform
initialization and type eliding... EXCEPT for default parameters (i.e.
N3139, DR 994, N3217). Which is annoying, as this is one of the most
interesting use cases. Oh, well; give the full type name so we still
build.

(It looks like N3139 wasn't implemented in GCC until 4.7. See also
https://gcc.gnu.org/bugzilla/show_bug.cgi?id=50209.)

Get color at image pixel

Add an additional accessor to vital::image to get the color at a
specified pixel as an rgb_color (which saves having to access each
channel value individually). See documentation for notes on assumptions
made w.r.t. the significance of image channels. (These assumptions are
expected to suffice for most cases.)

Throw exception on image out-of-range access

Modify pixel / byte accessors of image to throw an exception if the
requested address is out of bounds, rather than just asserting that it
is valid.

Modify triangulate_landmarks to set observations

Modify our generic landmark algorithm, triangulate_landmarks, to also
set the number of feature points used to compute each landmark (i.e.
number of observations).

This field was added recently, but our own algorithms were not setting
it. This should allow us to generate our own data that makes use of this
field.

Improve modification of landmarks

Fix some key spots where a landmark is recreated to construct the new
landmark as a copy of the old one, rather than only copying the location
and losing all other information not explicitly set. (In particular,
this is needed to preserve our new observation count.)

Fix reading rgb_color from an istream

Modify operator>>(istream, rgb_color) to read color channel values into
a temporary of type != unsigned char. This fixes reading the values
wrong due to istream::operator<<(char&) (and likewise for unsigned char)
reading single string characters rather than numbers.

See also eab51605c860 which fixes the exact same bug in a different
location. Sigh.
Update release notes

"Fix" channel order of OpenCV images

Modify how OpenCV images are mapped to vital images so that the channel
presented as 'first' is red, rather than blue. (This is done by tweaking
the first pixel offset and depth step; the in-memory order is not
changed.)

Improve enumerate_matrix tests

Add a test that iterators from the sparse matrix enumeration helper are
comparably distinct. This test is currently failing due to the
Eigen::SparseMatrix::InnerIterator lacking comparison operators(!), and
a nave implementation of our own iterator's operator== assuming that
they exist. (The code compiles due to an implicit(!) conversion of the
InnerIterator to bool.) This can result in SEGV's when the helper is
used with the fallback implementation of VITAL_FOREACH, due to the
previous and incremented iterator erroneously comparing equal (thus
breaking the innermost loop of the implementation which relies on being
executed exactly once).

Also add a test against empty sparse matrices (which were initially
believed to be causing the problem).

See also http://eigen.tuxfamily.org/bz/show_bug.cgi?id=1192

Generalized the image class to store different pixel types

The image class now stores a void pointer to the first pixel rather than
a byte pointer and a bytes_per_pixel field.  Methods have been updated
to handle different numbers of bytes per pixel.  The call operators have
been replaced with templated "at" functions similar to OpenCV.  Thus,
instead of

byte val = image(i,j);

we need to use

byte val = image.at<byte>(i,j);

A templated dervive class is also provided for convenience when the
image type is know.  This class is image_of<T> and has constructors and
member functions similar to the old image class.  For example

image_of<byte> img_b(100,100);
image img = img_b;
img_b(i,j) == img->at<byte>(i,j)
img_b.first_pixel() == reinterpret_cast<byte*>(img.first_pixel())

The C bindings have been updated to work with new image class, but do
not yet support differnt pixel types.

This commit also adds a new is_contiguous function to test for
contiguous memory blocks.  This is used to make deep copying of an image
faster with memcpy when the data is contiguous.

Use a faster method to get the Fully Qualified Domain Name

The previous approach was taking more than 30 seconds to get a FQDN on
some platforms.  The problem was that it iterated through each network
interface and did a domain lookup on each.  Some of these look-ups fail
but the timeout time is very long and non-configurable.

This alternate implementation is based on a suggestion on Stack Overflow:
http://stackoverflow.com/questions/504810/how-do-i-find-the-current-machines-full-hostname-in-c-hostname-and-domain-info

It uses getaddrinfo instead, which provides all the names upfront, so
don't need a look-up for each interface.

This code was generating the following warning:

false

null, it seems that should be handled elsewhere, e.g. before a NULL
pointer is converted to a reference.

Apply Necker reversal earlier in initialization

Waiting until the end to test for and correct Necker revsersal may
be too late to recover.  Reversal can't be detected if you try it too
soon.  This patch tries Necker reversal the first time the Necker
reversed initial RMSE is within the specified threshold of the
non-revsersed RMSE.  Whether we apply reversal or not, we only try it
once.

Replace matrix cast operator with .matrix() member function

New versions of Eigen implement a matrix constructor that takes precedence
over the matrix cast operator implemented on rotation, covariance, and
similarity.  This causes compilation errors.  This commit replaces the
cast operator with a more explicit .matrix() member function.

Enable thread safety in Cereal

Cereal is not thread safe by default, but provides a way to enable
thread safety at a small performance cost.  This commit enables thread
safety in Cereal by default.  Note that it is still not safe to access
one archive from multiple threads, but with this change it is safe to
access a different archive in each thread.

Add new geodesy types

Add "additional" geodesy types. These are intended to (eventually)
replace the existing lat/lon and UTM types, which must assume a CRS and
are less convenient to use. The new types are based on ViViA's geodesy
types, which define a geodetic location as a raw vector, and a CRS that
specifies how said vector relates to the Earth. This simplifies use by
having a single data type which does not impose a particular CRS or
style of representation and allows for more transparent on-demand
conversion between CRS's.

"Implement" geo-conversion interface

Geo-conversion is tricky. Because we want caching to be integrated into
the geodetic types (to prevent wanton misuse), the conversion functions
must also be members of the types. However, the implementation of
conversion requires PROJ or similar, which is contrary to our goal of
the types having minimal to no dependencies.

To work around this, add a globally registered conversion functor. This
allows an implementation (e.g. an arrow) to register itself as the
implementation of conversion so that the types can call such an external
implementation. (If no conversion functor is registered, conversions
will just fail.)

Implement geo-conversion for types

Now that there is an interface for doing so, add implementations to the
conversion functions of geo_point and geo_polygon. Note that this relies
on an underlying conversion operation, which is not yet implemented.

Remove comparison operators for new geodetic types

Remove the comparison operator declarations for geo_point and
geo_polygon. These were not yet implemented anyway, and strict equality
comparisons on geodetic points, and especially polygons, are even more
dubious than on single floating point values. (For example, one would
expect two instances of the "same" point stored in different CRS's to
compare equal, but actually making this happen is difficult. Until
someone has a strong use case, it seems better to simply remove the
operators.)

Make known CRS's not an enum

Convert well-known CRS SRID's from a class enum to a namespaced set of
int constants. After some attempts to use these in anger, it turns out
that an uncomfortable proliferation of static_cast would be required.

Implement geodetic conversion in PROJ

Add an implementation of geo_conversion in the PROJ arrow, and have the
arrow set itself as the conversion functor on load. This makes geodetic
conversion possible as long as the PROJ arrow is available.

(We'll probably need to revisit this if/when there are multiple
implementations available, but this should be good for the time being.)

Fix CSV parsing.

Multiple commas should not be treated as one comma in a CSV file. Thus, trimEmpty should be set to false when running the tokenizer on a line of a CSV file.

When detected_object_set_output_csv.cxx is used to create a CSV file of detections and no image file name is supplied, the second column will be correctly created as an empty column. That is, the file will contain a double comma in each line. When the parser in detected_object_set_input_csv.cxx ignores this column, it triggers the error test on line 224. In summary, the CSV writer and reader in arrows are not compatible with one another before this fix.

Add iterator interface to descriptors

Add an iterator/range (i.e. begin and end methods) to descriptors. This
allows them to be use in more ways, including standard algorithms and

Add release note for iterable descriptors

Refactor the track_set using a bridge design pattern.

This commit separates the interface from the implementation for the
track_set class.  The primary track_set class now dispatches all member
function calls to an implementation class contained within.  The
implementation class derives from the same interface and can support
multiple implementations.  The default implementation is the
simple_track_set_implementation.  This is the bridge design pattern and
it allows any derived track_set (e.g. feature_track_set or
object_track_set) to be used with any track_set implementation without
needing to explicitly implement all combinations.

Don't return rotation quaternion by reference

Change rotation::quaternion() to return by value, rather than returning
a reference to the internal data member. The latter is a subtle trap for
anyone calling the method on a temporary object; if the caller also
binds the return value to a reference, the resulting object will be
invalidated before it can be used. (In particular, this was causing many
of the VXL arrow tests to fail horribly because arrows/vxl/camera.cxx
was running afoul of this!)

Require C++11

Modify checks for C++11 features to trigger a configure error if
unavailable. This is consistent with our current requirement of a
reasonably C++11 compliant compiler and growing practice of assuming
that C++11 features are available (and thus using them unreservedly).

Assume std::chrono is available

Remove the configuration of the cpu_timer and wall_timer headers which
was present in case of older systems that lack std::chrono, since these
days we are assuming full availability of C++11. (This is also
consistent with the previous commit that turns lack of said features
into configure errors.) This will allow us to assume that these timers
are always available.

Also, fix a conditional check in wall_timer.h that provided a dummy
implementation unless a symbol was defined. This was redundant with the
configured-header approach, and worse, the symbol being checked was not
being defined anywhere, resulting in wall_timer never being available.

Import GoogleTest module

Import GoogleTest module from CMake 3.10. This provides dynamic
discovery of tests using Google Test, rather than the static discovery
used by older versions. Dynamic discovery is more robust and can handle
corner cases (particularly with respect to parameterized tests) that
static discovery cannot.

Note that this is not an exact copy of the upstream version, as upstream
uses CTEST_INCLUDE_FILES, which is also new in CMake 3.10. This version
employs a work-around using the older CTEST_INCLUDE_FILE. This has some
limitations if CTEST_INCLUDE_FILE is being used otherwise, but KWIVER is
not doing so and should thus be unaffected.

See also https://gitlab.kitware.com/cmake/cmake/merge_requests/1056.

Export more complete pixel traits

Add missing include

Use steady_clock for wall_timer

Change wall_timer to use std::chrono::steady_clock instead of
std::chrono::system_clock. The latter is great for getting a meaningful
"calendar" time, but is subject to random skew in either direction (e.g.
due to NTP adjustments or users changing the clock for whatever reason).
The former may give a time relative to an arbitrary and meaningless
point, but is (at least intended to be) monotonic. Since wall_timer only
cares about durations, this makes steady_clock more appropriate for its
use.

Fix config_block_set_value_cast<geo_polygon>

Fix algorithm to compute the correct number of decimal digits when
serializing a geo_polygon for output to a config_block. The previous
algorithm was failing to take the logarithm of the polygon magnitude,
such that we were setting the decimal digits precision to some screwy
value. For whatever reason, this apparently just happened to work on
Linux (possibly because it was producing a negative number that
libstdc++ ignored), but was causing Windows to output an empty string
instead of the coordinate value numbers.

Thanks go to the failing unit test for noticing that something was
wrong!

which existed for compatibility with older compilers (which we no longer
support).

object. Process properties were created based on the process class
hierarchy, where the derived process would create the set of
properties. There are cases where the derived process does not know
all the properties, such as when process instrumentation is
enabled. The solution is to add a set of properties that is part of
the process object that can accumulate these condition based
properties.

KPF YAML polygon I/O hack.

Back before YAML, the text-based KPF output wrote out polygons like this:

  poly0: 3 100 100 200 200 300 300

...where the '3' was the number of (x,y) points. However, the naive yaml
output:

   poly0: 3 [[ 10, 10 ],[ 20, 20 ],[ 10, 30 ],],

...is ill-formed. We just need to not emit the number of points:

   poly0: [[ 10, 10 ],[ 20, 20 ],[ 10, 30 ],],

...however, the upstream token parser REQUIRES the number of points.

The correct fix is to rework the upstream token parser to have more structure.

The quick hack fix is to (a) detect when we're parsing a poly and (b) insert
the number of tokens into the stream.

Since we don't support KPF non-YAML text output, git rid of the code for it.

KPF was bootstrapped in text mode until YAML came along; supporting complex

Fix per-configuration built-in plugin paths

Modify how we set up built-in plugin paths to perform substitution of
the `$<CONFIGURATION>` CMake generator expression in the C++ source
code. This is necessary because the configuration is not the final path
component (so we can't just tack on the configuration name to handle
per-configuration paths at the C++ level), and, since we can't pass the
list of paths directly as a defined symbol due to argument quoting
issues, because we are obtaining the paths through a configured file,
which cannot easily be made to contain per-configuration information.

This (along with the previous commit) should fix plugin loading on
multi-configuration generators (particularly Visual Studio) when relying
on the built-in paths, which in particular should fix the several dozen
tests that are currently failing because their needed plugins are
missing.

Squashed-for-review parsing of activities for track_oracle.

*Note that this branch tracks dev/kpf-track-oracle-activities,
unsquashed.*

This larger-than-I-would-have-expected set of commits all leads up to
this command functioning: (broken across lines for clarity):

   $ track_oracle/example/kpf_activity_example
       -in-geom ~/tmp/v3-geom.yml
       -in-act ~/tmp/v3-act.yml
       -out ~/tmp/bar

...in other words, track_oracle can now read and write KPF geometry
and activities.

1) A new KPF packet "cset" was added to represent classification
vectors; see kpf_example_simple_classifier (below) for an example.

2) The kpf_activity_example and kpf_example_simple_classifier binaries
was added.

3) The kpf_generic_reader binary was added.

4) Now requires the V3 KPF schema wrapper.

5) The KPF parser was basically completely rewritten (not my proudest
moment...)

Originally, KPF was a plaintext format. The late addition of YAML
solved a lot of problems (nesting structures, for example) but I
didn't think it through fully; in particular, the YAML record

     - { key1: val1, key2: val2, key3: val3 }

...is a map; you can't guarantee what order you'll see key1, key2, and
key3 as you iterate through the nodes. The old plaintext parser was
built around an ordered sequence of tokens, which failed miserably
once the record got large enough (i.e. activities). So it was ripped
out and rewritten.

Along the way the schema wrapper was added, bumping KPF's verison up
to V3.

This adds a *set* of confidence values as a map:

   cset17: { other: 0.1, person: 0.3, vehicle: 0.6, },

...now it could be argued that across thousands or millions of lines,
repeating the tags is wasteful, and we should have a cvec type:

   cvec17: { 0.1, 0.3, 0.6 }

...with the tags made explicit elsewhere. This is probably true,
but I'm really really afraid of slicing-n-dicing files and losing that
connection.

So now you can run (shown w/ abbreviated log messages):

$ track_reader_example -f ~/tmp/cset-geom.yml -kpf-g ~/tmp/quux.yml
INFO: Could not load default logger factory. Using built-in logger.

Modify embedded pipeline to allow config update before running.

In order to support inspecting, verifying and modifying the pipeline
config after the config has been ingested but before the pipeline has
been built, a method is added to allow derived classes to access the
config at the correct point in the execution.

This is useful in cases where the pipeline description must be read from
a file, but it must also meet specific requirements imposed by the
application. A derived class can implement the update_config() method
and verify that the requirements have been met, or add required entries
to the config before building the pipeline.

Work around potential bug in pybind, remove GIL-related code, use pybind's version

After creating a gil_scoped_acquire for the first time, we have to
call PyEval_SaveThread() to release the GIL. This commit also removes
some unnecessary GIL guards around PYBIND11_OVERLOAD() calls (since that
macro acquires the GIL automatically), adds call_guard<gil_scoped_release>
to the .def() calls, and removes some redundant GIL guards surrounding
the pystream calls. python_threading has also been removed so that we
are initializing threads in a single place.

Introduce range helpers

"Ranges" is a feature space of upcoming C++ (i.e. C++17 and later) that
simplifies common operations when working with sequences. Since it will
be some time before KWIVER can rely on native support, this starts
implementing some of the more useful bits ourselves.

As of this commit, integer sequences (which are useful for certain
classes of template functions) and a sliding window view are
implemented. The former is needed by the latter. The latter is wanted by
a unit test.

Upcoming commits will add additional features, including filtering and
transforming.

Introduce transform range adapter

Create a range adapter to apply a transformation to values of a range
during iteration. Introduce helpers to extract partial type information
from functors (needed to implement adapters that take a function).

Introduce filter range adapter

Create a range adapter to apply a filter to a range during iteration.
Adjust for latest master

Also work with non-class ranges

Add helpers to get the beginning and end of a range, and the iterator
types, for ranges that are not classes. This allows range adapters to
work with such types, e.g. raw arrays.

Make template adapters work on C-style arrays

...sort of. Template adapters, e.g. sliding, don't work on C-style
arrays prior to this commit, since it would require overloading
operator| for two pointer-type operands, which is not permitted (see
https://stackoverflow.com/questions/49638281). Unfortunately, right now,
I don't know of any way to make this work.

As a work-around, tweak the code so that it works if the adapter
function is invoked (i.e. `sliding<N>()` instead of `sliding<N>`). This
is a little aesthetically-challenged, but at least allows adapters to be
used as the first operation on a C-style array.
Add unit tests for range adapters
Add ranges release note

Allow default-construction of range iterators

Modify the range iterators to allow default construction and assignment.
The latter requires taking copies of the relevant functions for filter
and transform, and the former naturally produces a broken iterator
(though this is generally always the case for any iterator type), but
these changes are necessary to allow some combinations of chaining.

Generalize transform adapter function type

Modify transform_view to take the function type as a template parameter
rather than coercing the function into a std::function. This should
improve performance somewhat for certain functors, especially simple
function pointers. (This is more important since we now need to copy the
functor due to the previous commit.)

Force copies of range adapters

Create a reference-holder class for range adapters to use to hold the
"reference" to the input range. (This also allows some simplification of
how we obtain iterators.) Force this to take a copy if the input range
is itself a range adapter.

Copies of range adapters should be reasonably inexpensive, since they
are just holding iterators, functions, and the like. Taking a copy is
necessary to prevent intermediate adapters from being destroyed while
building an adapter chain. (Maybe one day C++ will solve lifetime
extension, and this will stop being a problem, but for now it's a
necessary evil.)

Change Doxygen preprocessor tag

Have Doxygen treat DOXYGEN as defined when parsing sources, rather than
DOXYGEN_IGNORE. The latter is not used being used anyway, and, as it was
being defined previously, would have rather the opposite effective
meaning as its apparent meaning.

Improve documentation of range adapters

Add some simple examples of using each of the range adapters. Tweak code
to hide implementation details from Doxygen so that the documentation
isn't cluttered by things that a user will never use directly.

Refactor function-type range adapter macros

Since 8e98df2689e2, there is no longer a difference in the utility
classes to construct a transform_view or a filter_view, and this will
probably hold true for other function-type views as well. Thus, refactor
the utility classes to make their definitions part of the implementation
helper macro, rather than requiring them to be defined per adapter.

Allow constexpr range adapters

Modify mechanisms that create range adapters to work in constexpr
contexts. While this does not fully allow use of range adapters in
constexpr context, it does allow declaration of a "canned" adapter as
constexpr. Critically, this lets us get rid of the inline adapter
as_object_track (inline variables being a C++17 feature which apparently
newer GCC is happy to accept even in C++11 mode) while theoretically
preserving the compiler's ability to inline through uses of the adapter.

Simplify range iterator type helper

Refactor the helper to obtain range iterator types to use a detail
namespace, into which all of std is imported. This is a little uglier in
some senses than doing the import into a function, but avoids needing to
obtain the return type of a lambda, which apparently doesn't work with
Visual Studio. (The resulting code is also markedly less esoteric, if
less elegant.)

Relevancy/confidence in 19th column should apply to frames, not tracks.

As written, when a 19th column is present in kw18, that value is
only applied to the track, not to the individual frames. So if you
have a track with three frames:

 track  frame   .... column-19

  1      10     ....  0.5
  1      11     ....  0.6
  1      12     ....  0.7

...then the relevancy will be assigned to track 1, and the value
will be the last one read (here, 0.7); the values of 0.5 and 0.6
are lost.

This fix applies the relevancy to the frames, not the track.

Since essentially the only use of having a 19th column in a kw18 is
to assign frame-level confidence values, and this is what the scoring
code expects, this will fix detection-mode scoring and shouldn't break
anything.

Remove const from range details

Remove explicit const qualification from range detail classes and
internal implementations. This will make it possible to implement range
adapters that can work on mutable ranges.

For now, all the existing adapters remain non-mutating.

Fix wrong-order test assertions

Fix order of arguments in the filter range adapter test. (These were in
the "natural" order actual, expected, but the macro wants expected,
actual... As this feels less natural, it is not too surprising that
these were backwards.)

Introduce indirect range adapter

Create a range adapter to apply a level of indirection to a range during
iteration. This effectively suppresses dereferencing of the iterator, so
that the user sees the iterators rather than the values, while still
being able to use the more terse and convenient syntax of a range-based
for. Also, fix some minor lingering issues with creating a mutating
range adapter.

Introduce validity range adapter

Create a range adapter to filter a range for valid items. This is
effectively the same as the filter adapter, except the filter function
is fixed as applying double-negation to the item. This is especially
convenient for iterating over a collection of pointers, in order to
visit only non-null pointers.

then, only when running the tests under valgrind.)

Force masks to binary with a threshold

Assuming mask image is intended to have values of only 0 and 255,
we can force masks into these values with a threshold at 128.  This is
important for compressed image sources where the values may not have
exactly the expected values.  The OpenCV code considers only 0 values
to be masked.  If the low values do not actually hit 0 then the mask
will not apply correctly.

Add process method to handle undefined ports.

This method supports dynamically creating ports as they are
specified making connections. The previous approach to dynamically
creating ports was to override the _*_port_info() method. While
this approach works, the _*_port_info() call is also called when moving
data over an edge. The derived implementation of this method can
add considerable overhead if it is not carefully programmed. In
addition, it is not obvious that the _*_port_info() calls are part of
the data transfer operations, so efficiency may not be part of the
design.

These new methods are only called when a port is being requested of a
process and it is not defined. They are never called again after the
port has been defined, eliminating the need to highly optimize these
methods.

more ranges (#721)

* Fix wrong-order test assertions

Fix order of arguments in the filter range adapter test. (These were in
the "natural" order actual, expected, but the macro wants expected,
actual... As this feels less natural, it is not too surprising that
these were backwards.)

* Introduce indirect range adapter

Create a range adapter to apply a level of indirection to a range during
iteration. This effectively suppresses dereferencing of the iterator, so
that the user sees the iterators rather than the values, while still
being able to use the more terse and convenient syntax of a range-based
for. Also, fix some minor lingering issues with creating a mutating
range adapter.

* Introduce validity range adapter

Create a range adapter to filter a range for valid items. This is
effectively the same as the filter adapter, except the filter function
is fixed as applying double-negation to the item. This is especially
convenient for iterating over a collection of pointers, in order to
visit only non-null pointers.

* Update release notes to mention new range helpers

Mention new range helpers added in the previous commits in the release
notes. Also, get rid of all the trailing whitespace in the release
notes, and fix an over-length line.

* Add additional range tests

Add a test that range::filter and range::valid work on empty input
ranges. Add a test that range::valid works on an input range with no
valid items.

* Don't crash on empty ranges

Fix issue with range::filter and range::valid that could cause a crash
if the input range is empty. (It seems that the compiler optimizations
are aggressive enough that the problematic code gets squelched in
release builds, so the problem only shows up in a debug build, and even
then, only when running the tests under valgrind.)

* Work around buggy ADL in VS

Move the range operators to the global namespace. This works around
buggy ADL in visual studio that apparently does not consider the
namespace of the RHS if the RHS is a function pointer. (GCC and Clang
don't have this bug.)

* misc range fixes

Reduced RANSAC triangulation inlier tolerance

When the tolerance was large many tests failed because they were just sticking
with the original guess that may have had 5 or 6 pixels of error when

2 pixels of error is more reasonable when the camera models are accurate.
However, we will likely need to increase this value when cameras are
less certain.

Fix failing triangulation tests due to inlier flag

Creating a projected track set now marks the projected tracks
as all inliers.  It's up to individual tests to now clear all

truth projected tracks were all consider outliers and we could
not measure the inlier RMSE error.

Update the KPF YAML parser to allow embedded YAML in metadata.

Some of the KPF coming out of the annotation toolchain contains
embedded YAML in the metadata, e.g.

   - { meta: { team: "Kitware" } }

...previously, the parser attempted to render the metadata as a
string via the as<string>() method. This fails for YAML objects, which
require a YAML::Emitter. So we first try the as<string>() approach; if
this fails, we use an emitter, which renders the above as

    meta '{team: !<!> Kitware}'

This parses to itself if used as input.

Correctly implement bitmask conversion

Add explicit conversion path for 'bool' (bitmask) images from Qt to

Also show text on pipeline viewer icons

Tweak pipeline viewer to always show text next to the toolbar icons.
This is helpful because, rather than fuss with supplying our own icons,
we took the easy route of relying on the system icon theme... which
works great (and is TRTTD) on XDG-compliant platforms, and not so well
on others (e.g. Windows, macOS). Always including the text may not be as
pretty, but at least won't have users scratching their heads wondering
about the blank buttons.

Default Qt use on Qt5_DIR instead

Change how we decide whether to enable Qt functionality by default to
look for Qt5_DIR (which should be set by fletch, if Qt 5 was built)
rather than just asking if fletch built Qt. The latter breaks if fletch
built Qt 4, while the former might also cause us to auto-enable e.g. if
the user is telling us where to find a non-system, non-fletch Qt.

Probes for missing KPF packets no longer invalidate the stream.

When the user calls reader.transfer_packet_from_buffer(), if it fails,
the reader should still be good. The catch is that the reader
also internally calls TPFB(); if called indirectly from the reader,
it should set the reader state to bad.

This commit adds a test case and adds an extra bool parameter to
TPFB (and the sibling transfer_kv_packet_from_buffer) which
defaults to false (don't change reader state) but is true
when called internally.

Treat empty detected_object_type like NULL d_o_t

Some processes, especially readers, create an new detected_object
with an empty, rather than NULL detected_object_type which prevents
them from being drawn by this process.  This change extends the
current behavior for a NULL d_o_t (essentially "just" a detection)
to include empty detected_object_types.

Be more forgiving when reading detected_object kpf

We'll only demand an ID, a Frame Number and a Bounding box
in each record (suffficent to build a detected_object).  We'll
more gently look for an Index (track id), detector_name and
confidence and use them if they're there.  Also update the
writer to write out detected_object->index.  This has the side
effect of allowing "GEOM" KPF annotation files from DIVA to
be read in as detected objects and provides enough information
(by adding index) to add annotation labels in a separate
process.

Update keyframe loop closure to store keyframes with the tracks.

Since this loop closure algorithm was written, the track set data structure
has been updated to stored frame-level data on the track set, including
a keyframe flag.  This commit updates the keyframe loop closure algorithm
to store the list of keyframes in the track set rather than internally.
This allows users of the tracks outside of this algorithm to know what
keyframes were selected.

Work around Visual Studio bug

Use size_t instead of int as the template type parameter when passing
around depth in the Qt image tests. This is necessary so that when the
parameter (via a class constexpr static member) gets passed to a
constructor that expects a size_t, the compiler doesn't have to
implement the exception of [dcl.init.list]/7.4, which Visual Studio
prior to VS2019 does not implement correctly.

See also https://developercommunity.visualstudio.com/content/problem/246960/msconnect-3131094-narrowing-conversion-from-int-co.html.

Make track_state::clone() fully deep copy

Modify clone() of classes derived from track_state (object_track_state,
feature_track_state) to have an option whether to make a full deep copy
(default, new), rather than continuing to share pointers with the
original state, or a shallow copy (previous behavior) which does share
pointers. This is necessary in order to e.g. make a copy of a
track[_state] that can safely be used by another thread. This also
affects the clone methods of track and track_set, those classes which
implement or derive from track_set, and the merge_in_other_track_set()
method of track_set. (Copy constructors still make only a shallow copy.)

This patch also incorporates several related improvements:

- Introduce a new helper class to keep references to the track_state's
owning track. This primarily has the behavior that it is non-assignable
and that copies don't actually copy anything. This allows more
operations on track_state itself to be defaulted.

- Improve the efficiency of track::clone() by reserving space in the new
history vector, rather than resizing. This avoids an extra
initialization of the history pointers.

- Improve the efficiency of simple_track_set_implementation::clone and
frame_index_track_set_impl::clone() by eliminating some unnecessary
smart pointer copies and a conditional which should always be true.

- Constructors which take r-value references to pointers to associated
objects are added to object_track_state and feature_track_state. (These
are used by the implementations of clone(), and save a reference
counting operation compared to the old constructors.)

Prevent modifying detection mask, descriptor

Modify detected_object to prevent modification to the mask or
descriptor, which rarely should be modified anyway. This makes it safe
to not deep copy these when cloning the detection.

Make detected_object's bounding box inline

Don't use a shared pointer to store the bounding box in detected_object;
instead, store it directly in the class. This is almost certainly less

scalars, which are trivial to copy by value, and this is consistent with
the constructor that takes each of {x,y}{min,max} individually, which
was already sensibly taking them by value.

Added a new parameter to depth integration for occluded space constant.

This new Epsilon value is used in the occluded portions of the volume
at a distance greater than Delta where the TSDF was previously defined to be
zero.  Using a very small positive value can be useful in preventing a
"shell" or "second surface" effect in which objects become hollow with
a thin shell because of the boundary between positive and zero values.
Setting Epsilon > 0 removes this second surface.

Epsilon > 0 is most useful when the depth viewpoint have coverage from all
angles.  When the depth viewpoint are limited, it may be better to set
Epsilon to 0.

Aggressively prevent reparenting track states

Track states differ from most objects in that they back-reference their
owning track. Accordingly, we prevent them from being added to a track
if they already have an owning track. However, users may not be aware of
this caveat (and indeed, multiple instances of this form of misuse have
been recently uncovered), and may not be checking for failures to add
track states to a track, since the "obvious" failure cases can often be
statically known to not occur.

In order to help address these issues, modify the code which adds track
states to make it a logic error (i.e. literally throw std::logic_error)
when attempting to add an already-owned track state to a track, as this
almost always indicates that the code attempting to perform the
operation does, in fact, contain a logic error. This should make it much
easier to identify such code, rather than having to chase down more
subtle bugs due to track states unexpectedly "going missing".

Mark intrinsics as fixed if any camera using them is fixed.

Because cameras can have shared intrinsics we should not optimize
the shared intrinsics if some cameras using them are fixed.
Those fixed cameras will have residuals ignored in the optimization
because they should be fixed, but they will actually change because
a non-fixed camera may adjust the shared intrinsics.  This causes
bundle adjustment to increase error in fixed cameras.  The safe
alternative is to only optimize intrinsics if all cameras sharing
the intrinsics are fixed.
added release note

Removed limit on number of fixed cameras in BA

This feature seems like a hack that could come back to bite us.
I don't think it belongs here in this current form.  As written,
the code filters residual terms after encountering 4 fixed cameras.
The residual terms added depends on the order the cameras are stored,
which is not a good thing.  A better way to write this would be to
first check if there are at least N fixed cameras and then choose to
filter all or none of the residuals based on that.  However, I'm not
convinced that that version of this feature is really needed either.

Added a filter to remove outliers in fundamental matrix matches

Filtering matches with a fundamental matrix tends to leave some

a second pass filter to remove a few large motions when the rest of
the matches have small motion.

When resectioning, use intrinsics from the nearest cameras

After bundle adjustment the intrincs may have changed from the initial
base camera.  If we then resection cameras we should used the bundle
adjusted intrinsics not the original base camera intrinsics.  Otherwise,
both the estimated pose and intrinsics will be further off and require
more bundle adjustment later to correct.

Avoid code duplication

Call set_callback instead of duplicating the code in that function.

Use callbacks with no data instead of no callbacks in BA.

Callbacks in BA serve two purposes:
 1. To provide state updates to the caller (e.g. GUI)
 2. To allow the user to terminate the optimization early

Purpose #1 can add expensive computation and is not always needed.
Purpose #2 is inexpensive and useful, even without #1.  This change
allows BA callbacks to optionally provide only #2.  It also updates
the keyframe initializer to use callbacks of type #2 rather than
disabling callbacks altogether.  This allows for early termination
with little extra cost.

Avoid using the subsample_cameras_favor_recent function.

Try to repair a fragmented camera graph

If the camera graph fractures into multiple connected components we were
previously discarding all but the largest component in hope that we could
rebuild it later.  In practice the discarded components can be large and
they do not get rebuilt.  This change tries to stitch the components back
together rather than discard them.  It finds the tracks that span across
the disjoint components and retriangulates them.  These points may be poorly
constrained, but they are required to hold the model together.

Added a second bundle adjuster instance to the initializer

The allows a separate "global" bundle adjuster instance that can be
configured differently.  The "global" BA instance is used for optimizing
all (or many) cameras at once that are already in good configuration.
The regular bundle adjuster is for correcting newly added cameras that
are less trusted.  With this change we can provided different optimization
paramters for each case.

The callback now takes a depth image, a status string, and

frame, but bundle adjustment would still try to use the constraints.
This would pull the solution apart because the constraints reference
frame is very differnt from the canonical transform reference frame.

Add a lower bound to non-max suppression radius.

If we get down to sub-pixel radii there is little further gain
and the run-time and memory cost grows greatly.
added function to compute the ground center of landmarks
added translation functions for maps of cameras and landmarks
added release note

Exposed the "force_common_intrinsics" option on keyframe initializer.

Also make this option "true" by default now.

Necker reverse newly resectioned cameras based on camera orientation.

The previous method used reprojection error to check for Necker reversal,
which is unreliable.

disable landmark merging

merge_landmarks is currently very very slow and it's not clear that
it is making a big difference in the quality of the solution.
This commit disables it for now.  We can turn it back on after
we investigate more.
refactor to make inlier threshold a parameter of retriangulate

Align the initial two cameras to constraints

We need the first two cameras to be properly upright before adding
a third so that we can properly reason about the third camera being
Necker reversed.

Avoid Necker reversal of the initial camera pair.

Evaluate both the original and Necker reversed solutions and take the one
with the lowest error.

After Necker reverse expand the retriangulation threshold and bundle adjust

This is needed to recover since Necker reversal often makes almost all
landmarks outliers
Disable windowed BA until the final stage when filling in cameras.
added release note

Do not update the base camera intrinsics with estimated values.

This can cause unexpected side effects. The base cameras is just an initial
guess.  If estimation produces a bad result we don't want to start from a bad
result in future iterations. Instead initialize intrinsics of new cameras from
existing cameras in the solution to make sure initial intrinsic match other
cameras.

This commit also corrects how intrinsics are shared depending on the value of
the force_common_intrinsics option.

Fixed a bug in which the closest camera was not found.

The last camera in the sequence was not used if it was the closest camera.
added release note

Apply Necker reverse to cameras individually rather than as a group.

Sometimes just a single camera gets flipped and we want to reverse it
even if the majority of cameras are not flipped.
Use only landmarks with 3 or more observations to estimate the scene plane.
Added a function to compute the subset of cameras on one side of a plane

Only Necker reverse if all cameras are above the landmark plane

If the plane passing through the landmarks also divides the cameras,
then the plane is likely estimated poorly.  If we try to Necker
reverse under these conditions the cameras on one side of the plane
will be reversed while the cameras on the other side will not.
added release note
improved log messages

Added new BA option for a minimum H-FOV

This is not a hard constraint on horizontal field of view, but a
strong soft constraint.  The residual cost term is zero when focal
length is in range but becomes quadratic for focal lengths above
the threshold set by this FOV.
added release note

Revert an earlier change to switch BA instances over time

Now that we switched to windowed bundle adjustment after establishing
keyframes, this hacky solution to reduce the number of BA iterations
when the solution gets large and near complete is no longer needed.
The windowed BAs tend to converge in just a few iterations anyway.
We don't want arbitrary thresholds on problem size to define when
to enforce fewer iterations.  Switching to windowed BA once keyframes
cameras are established does this implicitly in a better justified way.

Improve sorting by time

Improve the functionality to sort video_input_image_list's input
according to the images' timestamps, as introduced in the previous
commit. In particular, improve the configuration description to avoid
reference to a particular image reader wrapper, and improve the
performance of the sorting algorithm. Also, don't mix up the input
argument to sort_by_time with the member m_files. (They are always the
same, but doing so still makes the code unnecessarily obtuse.)

Benchmarking has strongly indicated that building a flat list with the
path and timestamp pairs, then sorting with std::sort, is faster in all
cases than either using std::map or rolling and unrolling a heap.
Additionally, the algorithm has been tweaked so that the paths are never
copied (because we are rebuilding the file list, we can move the strings
out of the input list into the scratch list, then move them back), which
should significantly reduce overhead from memory allocation. This
approach should require only a single allocation for the temporary
vector which will be sorted, which likely explains why it outperforms a
std::map which requires multiple node allocations. (It almost surely
doesn't hurt either to defer sorting until the entire list is complete
rather than sorting on every insertion.)

Fix camera initialization of principal point from metadata.

Previously metadata was used to initialize values for focal length and
principal point only if metadata for focal length was available.
In practice, we almost always have image size to initialize principal point
but have focal length data less often.  Since setting the principal point

added release note

Implement add_copy() method to take shared pointer.

An additional add_copy() method was needed to support python bindings. Python
manages objects with shared pointers and this collection did not support
that type of reference. An additional complication is that the metadata
collection manages its own elements and can not directly accept an element
managed by a shared_ptr due to the design of the collection. The metadata
item managed by the shared pointer is copied and the copy is added to
the collection. The copy is low overhead since metadata objects are
small, and metadata collections are not created that frequently.

Co-authored-by: Matthew Woehlke <matthew.woehlke@kitware.com>

Fixed a bug causing early termination of the camera init loop

The camera initialization loop is supposed to process all keyframes first
and when those are used up it processes the rest of the frames.  There
was a bug in catching this transition.  If the last keyframe camera failed
to initialized the loop would exit before switching to process the remaining
cameras.  The switching code has not been moved to the start of the loop
rather than the end to avoid this.
added a release note

Continue trying to register cameras until no further progress

Previously the algorithm attempted to add all key frames and then attempted
to add all other frames, never trying a camera more than once.  Often a camera
can be added later after its neighbors have been added.  With this change
we keep trying to add key frames until we pass through the residual key frames
without adding any more.  Then we keep trying to add the remaining frames
until we pass through the residual frames without adding more.  As a results
we typically get many more frames registered in the end.
added release note

Fixed improper RANSAC in OCV estimate_pnp causing low success rate.

For some reason there was an outer RANSAC loop around OpenCV's RANSAC algorithm
for PNP.  Each iteration called OpenCV RANSAC PNP with a max of 5 iterations.
The outloop iterated until at most 10000 iterations were called.
This was producing a rather low success rate for RANSAC.  Simply removing the
out RANSAC and letting OpenCV manage the same 10000 iteration budget produces
a sucessful solution much more often.

"Fix" class_map

Refactor class_map into a template class and reintroduce
detected_object_type (and activity_type) as explicit instantiations
thereof. This is necessary because the separate collections of types
also need to have separate global name maps and signals so that users
can differentiate between activity types and detected object types.

This also reverts a number of the changes made by e072724e5ed1 as they
are no longer necessary. (To wit, most places where detected_object_type
was changed to class_map are reverted, since detected_object_type exists
again, albeit now as a specific instantiation of class_map.)

Use Eigen3's CMake package

Remove our find module for Eigen and suppress use of the one that Eigen
itself ships, instead requiring the CMake package configuration. Use
Eigen's exported targets (which only exist using the package
configuration rather than the find module) instead of global includes.

This gets us a little closer to consumers being able to use KWIVER
without having to hack around our prior failure to export dependency on
Eigen. (Having public target includes instead of global includes would
be even easier, as this configuration currently requires that consumers
first find Eigen themselves, but that approach also breaks down if
consumers need to use Eigen from a different location. The proper fix is
for KWIVER's own package configuration to require Eigen, with a hint
where we expect to find it, but that's currently painful to do
correctly. This may be addressed in a future commit.)

Export our dependence on Eigen

Modify our CMake package configuration to export our dependence on
Eigen. This allows users to use our exported targets (which have public
dependencies on Eigen's targets) without having to find_package(Eigen3)
themselves.

Rename OpenCV version test symbols for clarity

Replace KWIVER_HAS_OPENCV_VER_{3,4} version test preprocessor symbols
with KWIVER_OPENCV_VERSION_MAJOR, which is defined to the major version
number of OpenCV (cuyrrently, `2`, `3` or `4`). This makes it clearer
when we have code that needs 3.x or newer, rather than the old setup
which implicitly (and perhaps confusingly) used the symbols to mean 'or
newer'.

Work around MOC bug

Rename some metadata items to work around a bug in Qt's MOC where it
chokes on macro arguments that start with numbers.

Even though this code doesn't use Qt itself, the issue makes it
impossible for Qt users to include this header, which can prevent Qt
applications from using KWIVER.

See also https://bugreports.qt.io/browse/QTBUG-87219.

Add configuration for uncrustify

Add a configuration for uncrustify to the repository. Add a note to
CONTRIBUTING.rst on its usage, including that it is currently considered
experimental.

"Apply" uncrustify to arrows/qt

Run uncrustify on arrows/qt and apply those changes that make sense.
This excludes a modest number of changes that should not have been made
and represent either bugs, configuration issues, or lack of desired
features. (For the latter, particularly, uncrustify currently does not
have a way to add blank lines between the start/end of a namespace and
content thereof while excluding blank lines in between different levels
of namespaces. On the other hand, I'm not sure if we're going to try to
implement this, or at some point just accept having blank lines there as
well, but for now, don't add them.)

Avoid global logger handles

When a logger handle is declared globally it causes the logger pluggins
to load and configure before entering the main function of a program.
This means main functions are not given any chance to configure logging
before the loggers are established.

Fixed a bundle_adjust parameter that was manually overridden.

The ceres bundle adjuster has an option update_state_every_iteration
that controls whether the state is updated on each iteration, generally
for the purpose of returning in a callback.  Previously we set this
option based on whether a callback was registered or not.  However, we
have since exposed this option in the algorithm config block.  There are
cases where we want a callback (e.g. to terminate early) but not updated
state.  However, we previously forgot to remove the old code that sets
this open based on whether a callback was set.  So the config option was
always overridden.

Fix high-pass filter for certain pixel types

Tweak the VXL high-pass filter to use a pixel-type appropriate type for
the accumulator instead of always using unsigned, which will work quite
badly for signed or floating point pixel types.

Note that this drops support for bitmaps (pixel type BOOL), for which
smoothing is a rather questionable operation anyway, and for 64-bit
integer pixel types, as these would require using a floating-point type
for the accumulator, which would need casts to avoid compiler warnings
and could result in non-trivial loss of precision. (The latter probably
is not a huge issue, but for now, it's unlikely we actually need to
operate on such images, anyway.)

Work around broken MSVC

Replace explicit lambda captures in the scale_image helper function of
vxl_convert_image with a default-capture-by-value specification. This is
needed to work around a bug in the MSVC compiler that conflicts with our
previous attempt (5fa46f9c338) to fix a warning about an unused capture.

The C++11 standard (n.b. the example at [expr.prim.lambda]12) is pretty
clear that capturing a constant from the containing scope is NOT needed,
however it seems that as of writing, a full decade later, no version of
MSVC implements this correctly.

Fixed flipped and transposed depth image memory

The code for loading depth images from a VTK file was storing the data both
flipped horizontally and transposed in the vital image.  The only user of
this data, CUDA depth fusion, was then transposing again during copy to
CUDA memory and flipping during pixel access to compensate.  This worked,
but any other algorithm using the same images would see the same garbled
memory and need would need to do the same operations to make sense of it.

This change removes the flip and transpose in both locations so that the
image passed in between is valid and can be used for other purposes.
added release note

Make end of pipeline detectable

Add EmbeddedPipelineWorker::finished signal to notify users when the
output endcap has received an end-of-input notification. This allows
better handling of pipeline completion for users that aren't tracking
completion based on number of frames processed. (This is also beneficial
to detect when the pipeline has halted if input is terminated
prematurely, as when aborting pipeline execution.)

Add KWIVER_CONFIG_PREFIX environment variable

Modify config search path logic to accept an environment variable
KWIVER_CONFIG_PREFIX as an addition to the normal KWIVER install prefix.
This provides a convenient mechanism for developers to ensure that
shared data from a build tree can be located. (This is more convenient
than KWIVER_CONFIG_PATH since our shared data is by default installed
to a version-specific location. Using KWIVER_CONFIG_PREFIX allows
pointing directly to the root of the build tree and does not need to be
changed when the KWIVER version changes.)

Fix track_features API

Alter track_features::track to take the frame as a frame_id_t rather
than as unsigned. Ironically, this isn't just "more correct", but

Also, tweak implementations to use the override keyword, which helps

Overhaul PROJ arrow, use PROJ 6 API

Overhaul the PROJ arrow to use the PROJ 6 API. We need to do this
eventually as the PROJ 4 API is deprecated and (as we recently started
doing) must be opted into for PROJ 6.x, and is removed entirely by PROJ
8.x.

This has some good bits, such as theoretically being thread safe, which
the old implementation probably was not. It also has a bunch of bad
bits, such as the number of cached projections now being O(N) rather
than O(N) (for N being the number of coordinate systems "in use"),
because the PROJ 5/6 API is, frankly, harder to use and in some ways
deliberately obtuse.

Refactor PROJ storage for destruction order

Refactor how we store thread-local information for the PROJ arrow to
ensure that the cached projections are destroyed before their associated
context. This fixes memory errors due to the destruction otherwise
potentially happening in the wrong order.

Never use public linking for bindings

vital_python_util), which we don't expect that anything will ever link
anyway, to always use PRIVATE linking. This improves consistency, as
most were already PRIVATE, but some for no apparent reason used PUBLIC
or even a mix of linking types.

Fix OCV inpainter modifying its inputs

Modify ocv::inpaint to avoid modifying the input images. Doing so is
unexpected and potentially dangerous, especially when the algorithm is
being used within a pipeline. Moreover, the manner in which we were
creating the output image container, which ultimately shared memory with
the input, was creating a divorced reference count, which could result
in the output becoming invalid when the input image container reference
count hits zero.

Avoid some smart pointer copying

Modify a handful of classes to add r-value reference overloads for
methods that take ownership of an object via a smart pointer. Add a
helper class to resolve overloads, which is needed for some of the
Python bindings.

Enable MVG on manual feature tracks

Modify initialize_cameras_landmarks implementation to make the minimum
number of tracks configurable. This is required to make it possible to
use the algorithm on manual feature tracks, which are likely to be
relatively few in number.

"Fix" keyframe selection

Modify initialize_cameras_landmarks to skip keyframe down-selection and
force use of all frames for initial reconstruction if the number of
input frames is smaller than the maximum number of keyframes to use.
This is required because the down-selection process will otherwise
down-select to an empty set if only a few frames have tracks, which will
be the case if the input is not video, or if only a few frames have
features when using manually annotated feature tracks.

Add check in find_track that it returned a valid result

We check the result of calling std::lower_bound because it isn't
guaranteed to find an equal result.

This could theoretically matter in two cases: first, if we forget
about a track but then receive it as input again, and second, if
incoming tracks are not numbered increasingly.

Update ref_loc based on the feature location

If ti describes an active track whose reference frame is not the
current frame, using the reference location is a mistake because
output->homography() maps /current-frame/ coordinates to
reference-frame coordinates.  fts->feature->loc() provides current
information.

Remove redundant invocations of vector_2d

Fix regression prevention check in compute_ref_homography_core

winner (earliest_ref).

Finish computing matches before modifying the feature tracks

If not, there's at least one issue due to threading, namely that the
call to merge_tracks can ultimately call erase on
simple_track_set_implementation::data_, which can cause the call to
simple_track_set_implementation::tracks, which copies data_ and is
indirectly made by match_tracks, to copy data_ while elements are
actively being removed from it.  This manifests as empty shared_ptrs
in the return value of tracks that are dereferenced in
track_set_implementation::active_tracks to cause a segfault.

Don't rely on implicit inclusion of cstdint

Explicitly include <cstdint> in headers using uint8_t. Expecting it to
be indirectly included isn't reliable and can lead to build failures.

Don't use value uninitialized

Add explicit initialization of local variable in order to avoid a
compiler warning that the value may be used uninitialized.

Add missing include to class_map

Explicitly include <string> in class_map.h. Expecting it to be
indirectly included / relying on forward declarations of std::string is
unreliable and in some instances results in extremely obscure error
messages regarding partial specialization of standard-library hash
entities.
